Time Series: Example 1

Samuel Burer (samuel-burer@uiowa.edu)

Updated: July 28, 2021

Preparation

If you are following along in RStudio, to prepare for this example, choose the RStudio menu item Session > Restart and Clear Output. Alternatively, you can choose Run > Restart R and Clear Output in the notebook code window. You will also need to install the ggplot2 and forecast packages and to source code_Time_Series.R.

# install.packages(c("ggplot2", "forecast")) # Paste into console to install
source("code_Time_Series.R")

Data and Getting Started

The file data_Time_Series.Rdata contains several time series that will be the basis of our example. In particular, we will work only with univariate time series, i.e., time series that contain just one column of data. Lets load the data:

The data sets are as follows:

  • cpi = annual Consumer Price Index since 1947, which is indexed to the value 1.0
  • elec = monthly net electricity generation in the U.S. (in kWh)
  • google = daily closing price (in $) of Google stock (start date = February 25, 2013)
  • lettuce = monthly Producer Price Index for lettuce since 1947; the average of 1982 is indexed to 100.0
  • qc = quality control data; 5 measurements per day, for 25 consecutive days; measurements are taken at 6:00, 10:00, 14:00, 18:00, and 22:00
  • rain = annual rainfall (in inches) in Philadelphia
  • soda = monthly soda sales (in thousands of cases) for a soda distributor
  • ui = total Fall plus Spring semester enrollment at the University of Iowa

In the code chunk below, you can uncomment whichever series you would like to work with in this example. Then the time series will be referenced in the object called myts throughout this example.

Lets first look at the raw data:

myts
     Jan Feb Mar Apr May Jun Jul Aug Sep Oct Nov Dec

1999  35  40  46  55  60  68  72  75  70  66  58  50
2000  45  49  57  68  78  80  88  90  84  80  57  60

The command autoplot(...) can be used to provide a quick plot of the time series.

autoplot(myts)

#autoplot(efficiency)

If the time series exhibits unstable variation (or unstable fluctuation) over time, you should log the time series. You should also log the time series if you suspect an exponential trend over time. If so, you can uncomment the following two lines to resave myts in logged form and print a new plot.

myts <- log(myts)
autoplot(myts)


#efficiency <- log(efficiency)
#autoplot(efficiency)

If you do decide to log your time series, then keep this in mind for the rest of the example. Any analysis will be in the log, and youll need to do exp to get the analysis back in the original data.

Exploration

Before doing any sophisticated analysis of a time series, it is important to get a basic feel for the data. One of the best ways is to look at the decomposition of myts, which breaks the time series down into a trend component, a seasonal component (as applicable), and a remainder component. Pay attention to the \(y\) scales in the decomposition plot!

decomp <- mstl(myts)
autoplot(decomp)


#decomp_efficiency <- mstl(efficiency)
#autoplot(decomp_efficiency)

Its also helpful to know if the series has any autocorrelation issues, which can be viewed using the Acf(...) function. Note the capital letter A but lowercase letters cf. Autocorrelation can also reveal any seasonality patternswhich you may or may not already be aware of.

Acf(myts)
